data.content:
In .NET 11 (EF Core 11), the **sync-over-async opt-in for the Cosmos DB provider is removed entirely**. Every synchronous LINQ operator and `SaveChanges()` call will throw an `InvalidOperationException` — there's no configuration to re-enable it.

**What breaks:** All four methods — `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, and `SaveChanges()`.

**The fix** is to convert to async:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- The underlying Cosmos DB SDK has always been async-only; EF was masking this with internal `Task.Run`/`.Result` blocking, which risks deadlocks and thread-pool starvation.
- `Add()` is a pure in-memory operation on the change tracker, so it stays synchronous — only the database round-trip (`SaveChangesAsync`) needs the change.
- You'll need to propagate `async/await` up through your call chain (controllers, services, etc.).
